  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Indonesia Cooperative Business Development Alliance (ICBDA)</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The overall goal of the ICBDA project is to increase employment and income for men and women through increased production and marketing of high-value crops, namely cassava, black and white pepper, clove and vanilla in underdeveloped regions of West Timor, South Sulawesi and the northern coast of Papua. The program is increasing their production, post-harvest handling and processing, and marketing by strengthening existing agricultural cooperatives and establishing viable marketing channels and partnerships. 

These supply chains are managed by an alliance of cooperatives at Indonesian local and national levels together with PT Cooperative Business International Indonesia and several of its Indonesian joint venture affiliates. The black and white pepper, clove and vanilla supply chains link smallholder farmers to McCormick and Company and subsidiaries, which comprise by far, the largest spice company in the world.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Train farmers in new techniques and technologies for producing cassava, black and white pepper, clove and vanilla (9,898 farmers have now been trained and applied new technologies and techniques in the three regions. This is nearly double the target of 5,550 farmers)</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">men and women from Indonesia&apos;s agricultural cooperatives</narrative>
  </description>
